GAINS consisted of 8 large-volume high-purity Ge
detectors (only 7 of them were active ) placed at 110
and 150 deg with respect to the beam direction, with
four detectors at each angle, at distances of 14-16.5cm
from the target.
Gamma energy resolution - 2.3 keV for the 1332 keV peak
of 60Co and 100% relative efficiency.
The calibration measurements were taken with a
point-like 152Eu source ( activity 18.9 +- 0.6 kBq).
The determination of the setup efficiency was performed
by a method combining calibration measurements and
MCNP5 simulations.
The neutron flux was monitored with a 235U
fission chamber placed in the measurement station.
For the threshold used in this measurement the
efficiency of the fission chamber was 84+-2 %.
The statistical uncertainties of the detector
yields ~ 2%.
Uncertainty due to HPGe efficiency calibration
(mainly from the activity of the source and the
positioning of the calibration source) - 2% .
The uncertainty of the multiple scattering
correction factor calculated from the MCNP5 simulations
Uncertainty of 235U(n,F) cross section from
ENDF/B-VII.1 - 0.7%.
Uncertainty of the fission chamber efficiency
The total resulting uncertainty for the
strongest transitions is of the order of 5% .
ToF facility GELINA.
Station located 200 m from the neutron source.
GAINS (Gamma Array for Inelastic Neutron Scattering)
setup.
Electrons accelerated to 70-140 MeV with a
repetition rate of 800 Hz and a FWHM of the pulse <1ns
bremsstrahlung in a rotating depleted uranium target.
The neutrons are produced through U(g,xn) and U(g,f)
reactions. Neutron beam was collimated to a diameter of
61 mm and the energy-integrated flux was ~ 500 n/cm2/s.
Two filters were used:
- natU (36.8 g/cm2),
both placed in the middle of the source-sample distance
to avoid moderated neutrons and to attenuate the gamma
flash proceeding the neutron pulses.
Neutron energy resolution of ~1 keV at 1MeV and up to
~ 35 keV at 10MeV .
The differential gamma production cross section at
angles of 150. and 110. deg in the energy range from
threshold energy up to 18 MeV were measured.
The angle integrated gamma production cross sections
were determined in the same energy range.
The total inelastic cross section and the level cross
sections were calculated using the low excitation
energy level scheme of 24Mg from the evaluated
database.
24Mg sample of diameter of 8.003 +- 0.001 cm, area
density of 0.698 +- 0.001 g/cm2, was irradiated at a
distance of 19868.4 cm from the neutron source.
Approved by the author A.Olacel 04.02.2015.
Level density was deduced by direct counting of the
resonances .
